# The APSIM-NextGen Lucerne Model

Xiumei Yang(1), Hamish Brown(1), Edmar Teixeira(1), Derrick Moot(2)

-1 Plant & Food Research

-2 Lincoln University

## History:
The lucerne model is based on the APSIM classic v 7.10 (**Robertson et al 2002**) with calibration from **Moot et al 2015** and **Yang (2021) implementation within the Plant Modelling Framework **(Brown et al 2014)**.   

- Brown H et al. 2014. Plant modelling framework: software for building and running crop models on the APSIM platform. Environ. Model. Softw. 62:385-398. doi: 10.1016/j.envsoft.2014.09.005.

- Moot DJ, Hargreaves J, Brown HE, Teixeira EI. 2015. Calibration of the APSIM-Lucerne model for ˜'Grasslands Kaituna' lucerne crops grown in New Zealand. New Zeal. J. Agric. Res. 58(2): 190-202.

- Robertson MJ et al. 2002. Simulation of growth and development of diverse legume species in APSIM. Aust. J. Agric. Res. 53(4): 429-446. https://doi.org/10.1071/AR01106.

- Yang, X. 2020. Modelling phenological development, yield and quality of lucerne (Medicago sativa L.) using APSIM next generation. PhD thesis, Lincoln University, Canterbury, New Zealand.

- Yang X, Brown HE, Teixeira EI, Moot DJ 2021. Development of a lucerne model in APSIM next generation: 1 phenology and morphology of genotypes with different fall dormancies. European Journal of Agronomy 130, 126372.

- Yang X, Brown HE, Teixeira EI, Moot DJ 2022. Development of a lucerne model in APSIM next generation: 2 canopy expansion and light interception of genotypes with different fall dormancy ratings. European Journal of Agronomy 139, 126570.

- Yang X, Brown HE, Teixeira EI, Moot DJ 2023. Development of a lucerne model in APSIM next generation: 3 Biomass accumulation and partitioning for different fall dormancy ratings. European Journal of Agronomy 142, 126665.

Children.Text:
## Summary and details of current phenological stages and codes are:

1 - Sowing

2 - Germination

3 - Emergence       (visible seedlings)

4 - End of Juvenile (regrowth crops are re-set to this stage after defoliation)

5 - Floral initiation (bud-visible stage)

6 - Start Flowering  (visible early-flowers stage)

7 -Start pod fill (not tested)

8 - Maturity (not tested)

9 - Ripenning (not tested)

## The phenological phases are:

Juvenile: 3 to 4 (Reproductive development is not sensitive to photoperiod)

Inductive: 4 to 5 (Reproductive development is sensitive to photoperiod)

Induced: 5 to 6 (Reproductive development was induced)

Flowering: 6 to 7

Podfilling: 7 to 8

Ripening: >8

## Observations:

- Estimate for Flowering and Podfilling and Ripening of 1,500 oCd, which is not tested.

Radiation use efficiency (RUEtotal) for total DM (DMtotal; shoot plus toproot biomass) was calculated from the linear regression of DMtotal against accumulated intercepted radiation for each regrowth cycle, where the slope of the linear regression represents RUEtotal. The calculated values for RUEtotal were then used to develop the function of RUEtotal in response to mean air temperature.

Reference:

Children.Text:
Empirical parameterisation of lucerne LAI with the "simple leaf" class. 

**Context:** 

- This is a first step towards a "simple leaf" LAI model that is still empirical without representing individual leaves and canopy components. 
- The **Leaf Area** node in simple leaf is same as **LAI (m2 leaf/m2 soil)**
- LeafArea is accumulating daily fractions of LAI **(DeltaLAI)** and subtracting it from Senescence (**SenFracLAI**) and frost damage (**FrostDeath**)

**Assumptions:**

- Plant population is optimum for canopy expansion (i.e. plants x shoots/plant x branches/shoot x leaves/shoot or branch compensate to potential rates)

- Other empirical adjustment factors minimise LAI expansion rates to **actual** values by simple fractional adjustments.

## Leaf Nitrogen dynamics

**NDemand** is in **g N/m2 per day**

- 100% of leaf N is available to other organs after sensecence **NRealalocation = 1** 
- 0% N in storage **NRetrsnslocation = 0** 

- Maximum leaf N% is parameterised based on empirical data from Lincoln University and aligned with Lemaire et al 1992 allometric "slow" decay with above-ground biomass.
- Critical and Minimum N% are assumed as fractions of maximum N% at a given above-ground biomass


Lemaire, G., Khaiti, M., Onillon, B., Allirand, J.M., Chartier, M., Gosse, G., 1992. Dynamics of accumulation and partitioning of N in leaves, stems and roots of lucerne (Medicago sativa L.) in a dense canopy. Ann. Bot. 70, 429-435.

Children.Text:
DMDemands in **g/m2 per day**

**Note:** Structure and parameterisaion for a dynamic seasonal taproot biomass are under test - see context below. 

**Rationale:**

- TapRoot has **Structural and Storage tissues** (i.e. no Metabolic)

**Assumptions:**

**1. Input "demand" for biomass:**

- There is a **minimum "structural" taproot biomass** possible per plant (e.g. 0.8 g /plant x plant pop = 2.5 t/ha for a 300 plants/m2 pop) 
- **Structural demand** grows taproot at a max of 1% of gap between actual and mimimum structural, until min structural/plant is achieved.
- **Storage demand** depends on storage "capacity" which is proportional to available structural taproot biomass (**XXX = 5** or ~17% of taproot) 

**2. Output "desapearance" of taproot biomass:**

- **Storage demand** is reduced at decreasing photoperiod (winter/spring) but fixed at 100% at increasing Pp. 
- Taproot biomass is then consumed via **Retranslocation (to shoots) or MaintenceRespiration (to void)**
- **DMRetranslocationFactor** is a maximum fraction of storage N available per day for retranslocation (1%/day)
- **Maintenencece respiration** is linearly responsive to TapRoot protein content (1 to 2%/day)

**3. Issues:**

- Retranslocation logic **requires documentation/ref**
- References for root dynamics logic **(seasonality and respiration)** given bellow 

**4. References:**

Atkinson, L.J., Hellicar, M.A., Fitter, A.H., Atkin, O.K., 2007. Children.Text:
The logic here is:

- Assume a mimimum amount of structural biomass
- Create demand to reach this target if current amount is less than that
- Assumes that 1% of potential difference is "demanded" by day 
- Assumes a maximum 2.5 t/ha of taproot

Children.Units: minimum share of structural in taproot
Children.Name: StructuralFraction

Children.Text:
The logic here is:

- Assumes a mimimum of 20% **StructuralFraction** biomass in taproot - so a **PotentialStorage** of 80% DM
- Compares current Storage with PotentialStorage (**StorageGap**)
- Allows a **MaxDailyStorageRate** as a fraction of the StorageGap (g DM/m2 per day)
- MaxDailyDemand is a first try to ensure we do not have exess demands per day - needs check FIXME
